message_1:
Consider the system of nonlinear equations:
\begin{aligned} 
e^{-x^2+y}+x^2+y^3 &=3 \\ 
x^3-xy^2+2y-1 &=0 
\end{aligned}

Use Newton's method to find the solution $(x, y)$ starting with the initial approximation $(x_0, y_0) = (1, 1)$. Use the tolerance of $10^{-5}$ and perform a maximum of 10 iterations.

message_2:
To apply Newton's method to this system of nonlinear equations, we first need to compute the Jacobian matrix of the system, which consists of the partial derivatives of the functions with respect to the variables x and y:

\begin{aligned}
J(x, y) = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(e^{-x^2+y}+x^2+y^3) & \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(e^{-x^2+y}+x^2+y^3) \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(x^3-xy^2+2y-1) & \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(x^3-xy^2+2y-1)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}

Computing the partial derivatives, we get:

\begin{aligned}
J(x, y) = \begin{bmatrix}
-2xe^{-x^2+y}+2x & e^{-x^2+y}+3y^2 \\
3x^2-y^2 & -2xy+2
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}

Now, we apply Newton's method using the initial approximation $(x_0, y_0) = (1, 1)$, the tolerance of $10^{-5}$, and a maximum of 10 iterations. The iterative formula for Newton's method for systems of nonlinear equations is:

\begin{aligned}
\begin{bmatrix}
x_{n+1} \\
y_{n+1}
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
x_n \\
y_n
\end{bmatrix}
-
J(x_n, y_n)^{-1}
\begin{bmatrix}
e^{-x_n^2+y_n}+x_n^2+y_n^3-3 \\
x_n^3-x_ny_n^2+2y_n-1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}

Applying the formula iteratively:

Iteration 1:
$(x_0, y_0) = (1, 1)$
$J(1, 1) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 4 \\ 2 & 0 \end{bmatrix}$
$J(1, 1)^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0.5 \\ -0.5 & 0 \end{bmatrix}$
$\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ y_1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0.5 \\ -0.5 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1.5 \end{bmatrix}$

Iteration 2:
$(x_1, y_1) = (1, 1.5)$
$J(1, 1.5) = \begin{bmatrix} -0.73576 & 10.73576 \\ -0.5 & -1 \end{bmatrix}$
$J(1, 1.5)^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} -0.09524 & -1.02381 \\ -0.04762 & -0.08810 \end{bmatrix}$
$\begin{bmatrix} x_2 \\ y_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1.5 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} -0.09524 & -1.02381 \\ -0.04762 & -0.08810 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -0.73576 \\ 0.5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1.00000 \\ 1.04444 \end{bmatrix}$

Iteration 3:
$(x_2, y_2) = (1.00000, 1.04444)$
$J(1.00000, 1.04444) = \begin{bmatrix} -0.00000 & 4.13222 \\ 1.00000 & -0.08889 \end{bmatrix}$
$J(1.00000, 1.04444)^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} -0.00000 & 0.24074 \\ -0.46296 & -0.00000 \end{bmatrix}$
$\begin{bmatrix} x_3 \\ y_3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1.00000 \\ 1.04444 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} -0.00000 & 0.24074 \\ -0.46296 & -0.00000 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 0.00000 \\ 0.04444 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1.00000 \\ 1.00000 \end{bmatrix}$

Since the change in the variables is less than the tolerance of $10^{-5}$, we can stop the iterations here. The solution is $(x, y) = (1.00000, 1.00000)$.
